Here’s a project we developed for the Reefscape season and how you can build it:

First, you can view our code on GitHub: [github.com/Giro-FRC/AdvantageKitSwerve](https://github.com/Giro-FRC/AdvantageKitSwerve).  

The core concept is straightforward: detect which field zone the robot is in and automatically align it to the nearest reef. This requires robust odometry, so we recommend integrating a vision system. Let’s get started.

### 1) Automatic Path Generation  
We use PathPlanner to create paths on-the-fly. In a dedicated class (e.g., `GoToPath`), you define a function that takes the robot’s current pose and a target pose, supply reef-alignment points, and let PathPlanner compute the optimal path.

**Note:** We also have this helper function mirrored in our `AutoAlignment` class to keep alignment logic centralized.

```java
package frc.robot.commands;

import com.pathplanner.lib.auto.AutoBuilder;
import com.pathplanner.lib.path.PathConstraints;
import edu.wpi.first.math.geometry.Pose2d;
import edu.wpi.first.math.util.Units;
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.Command;
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.CommandScheduler;
import frc.robot.subsystems.drive.Drive;
import org.littletonrobotics.junction.Logger;

public class GoToPath extends Command {
  private final Drive drive;
  private CommandScheduler scheduler;
  private final Pose2d targetPose;

  public GoToPath(Drive drive, CommandScheduler scheduler, Pose2d targetPose) {
    this.drive = drive;
    this.scheduler = scheduler;
    this.targetPose = targetPose;
    addRequirements(drive);
  }

  @override
  public void initialize() {
    PathConstraints constraints = new PathConstraints(3.0, 3.0, Units.degreesToRadians(540), Units.degreesToRadians(720));
    Logger.recordOutput("GoToPath/RobotPose", drive.getPose());
    Logger.recordOutput("GoToPath/TargetPose", targetPose);

    Command pathfindingCommand = AutoBuilder.pathfindToPose(targetPose, constraints, 0.0);
    scheduler.schedule(pathfindingCommand);
  }

  @override
  public void execute() {}

  @override
  public void end(boolean interrupted) {}

  @override
  public boolean isFinished() {
    return true;
  }
}
```

### 2) Defining Field Zones  
To locate the robot on the field, we define each area of interest as a polygon. In the `FieldPolygon` class:
- List corner points (X–Y coordinates)
- Combine them to form shapes
- Check at runtime if the robot’s pose is inside any polygon

The result might look like this:  
![image](https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/4X/0/9/b/09b366eb3069ec72fb9059d86bed7ba6643ca0bb.png)

```java
package frc.robot.util;

import edu.wpi.first.math.geometry.Pose2d;

public class FieldPolygon {
  public int checkRobotPosition(Pose2d robotPose) {
    double x = robotPose.getX();
    double y = robotPose.getY();

    if (x >= 4.501 && x <= 8.768 && y >= 6.176 && y <= 8.000) {
      return 1;
    } else if (x >= 4.501 && x <= 8.768 && y >= 1.902 && y <= 6.176) {
      return 2;
    } else if (x >= 4.501 && x <= 8.768 && y >= 0 && y <= 1.902) {
      return 3;
    } else if (x >= 0 && x <= 4.501 && y >= 0 && y <= 1.240) {
      return 4;
    } else if (x >= 0 && x <= 4.501 && y >= 1.240 && y <= 6.760) {
      return 5;
    } else if (x >= 0 && x <= 4.501 && y >= 6.760 && y <= 8.000) {
      return 6;
    } else {
      return 0;
    }
  }
}
```

### 3) Zone Detection & Nearest Reef Alignment  
The final piece is in your `AutoAlignment` class. Every loop:
- Read the robot’s current pose
- Determine which zone contains that pose
- Find the nearest reef-alignment point
- Schedule a command to drive to the reef

This simple logic lets the robot automatically choose—and align to—the closest reef when it enters its zone.

```java
package frc.robot.commands;

import com.pathplanner.lib.auto.AutoBuilder;
import com.pathplanner.lib.path.PathConstraints;
import edu.wpi.first.math.geometry.Pose2d;
import edu.wpi.first.math.geometry.Rotation2d;
import edu.wpi.first.math.util.Units;
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.Command;
import frc.robot.subsystems.drive.Drive;
import frc.robot.util.FieldPolygon;
import org.littletonrobotics.junction.Logger;

public class AutoAlignment extends Command {
  private final Drive drive;
  private final FieldPolygon fieldPolygon = new FieldPolygon();
  private final boolean left;

  public AutoAlignment(Drive drive, boolean left) {
    this.drive = drive;
    this.left = left;
    addRequirements(drive);
  }

  @override
  public void initialize() {
    PathConstraints constraints = new PathConstraints(3.0, 3.0, Units.degreesToRadians(540), Units.degreesToRadians(720));

    int area = fieldPolygon.checkRobotPosition(drive.getPose());
    Logger.recordOutput("Robot Area", area);

    Pose2d targetPose = new Pose2d();
    if (area == 1) {
      targetPose = new Pose2d(5.152, 5.183, Rotation2d.fromDegrees(-120));
    } else if (area == 2) {
      targetPose = new Pose2d(5.835, 3.966, Rotation2d.fromDegrees(180));
    } else if (area == 3) {
      targetPose = new Pose2d(5.212, 2.882, Rotation2d.fromDegrees(120));
    } else if (area == 4) {
      targetPose = new Pose2d(3.846, 2.882, Rotation2d.fromDegrees(60));
    } else if (area == 5) {
      targetPose = new Pose2d(3.148, 4.025, Rotation2d.fromDegrees(0));
    } else if (area == 6) {
      targetPose = new Pose2d(3.816, 5.168, Rotation2d.fromDegrees(-60));
    }

    AutoBuilder.pathfindToPose(targetPose, constraints).schedule();
  }

  @override
  public void execute() {}

  @override
  public void end(boolean interrupted) {}

  @override
  public boolean isFinished() {
    return true;
  }
}
```

